{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641813","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641813"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:32:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:32:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17905"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17905"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.38,0.29,0,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10619"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78728"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10619"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17905"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64071"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10049"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24743"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24746"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27006"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78728"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe L cells are located along most of the length of the gastrointestinal tract, with highest density in the mid small bowel. One particular hormone produced by these cells signals satiety and slows gastric emptying.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is this hormone?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cholecystokinin","Glucagon-like peptide-1","Ghrelin","Insulin","Peptide YY"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeptide YY (PYY)\u003C/strong\u003E is a hormone produced by L cells in the intestine and acts as a satiety signal. It is released postprandially and helps reduce appetite by slowing gastric emptying and inhibiting gut motility.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucagon-like peptide-1 (GLP-1)\u003C/strong\u003E is also produced by L cells and has a role in satiety, but the question specifically asks for the primary satiety signal, which is PYY.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECholecystokinin (CCK)\u003C/strong\u003E is produced by I cells in the duodenum and jejunum, not L cells. It also contributes to satiety but is not the primary hormone produced by L cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsulin\u003C/strong\u003E is produced by the beta cells of the pancreas and plays a role in glucose metabolism rather than directly acting as a satiety signal from the intestine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGhrelin\u003C/strong\u003E is a hormone that stimulates appetite and is produced mainly in the stomach, not by L cells in the intestine.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Peptide YY (PYY) and glucagon-like peptide-1 (GLP-1) are satiety signals produced by L cells in the intestine.","Cholecystokinin (CCK) is produced by I cells in the duodenum and jejunum, not L cells.","Insulin is produced by the beta cells of the pancreas and is not a direct satiety signal from the intestine."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Judge A, Dodd MS. Metabolism. Essays Biochem. 2020 Oct 8;64(4):607-647. doi: 10.1042/EBC20190041. PMID: 32830223; PMCID: PMC7545035","Austin J, Marks D. Hormonal regulators of appetite. Int J Pediatr Endocrinol. 2009;2009:141753. doi: 10.1155/2009/141753. Epub 2008 Dec 3. PMID: 19946401; PMCID: PMC2777281","Hernando-Redondo J, Toloba A, Benaiges D, Salas-Salvad\u00f3 J, Mart\u00ednez-Gonzalez MA, Corella D, Estruch R, Tinahones FJ, Ros E, Goday A, Casta\u00f1er O, Fit\u00f3 M. Mid- and long-term changes in satiety-related hormones, lipid and glucose metabolism, and inflammation after a Mediterranean diet intervention with the goal of losing weight: A randomized, clinical trial. Front Nutr. 2022 Nov 18;9:950900. doi: 10.3389/fnut.2022.950900. PMID: 36466401; PMCID: PMC9716624","Yeung AY, Tadi P. Physiology, Obesity Neurohormonal Appetite And Satiety Control. 2023 Jan 3. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32310366"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64071"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17905"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64071"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T15:21:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T15:22:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10619"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78728"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"d